> Also, I happily went and added all my readonly tags to a [Serializable] class only to discover (of course) that a binary deserialize will fail in this instance due to the readonly property. But NO warning of this until the runtime error.

_Originally posted by @vsfeedback in https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/27212#issue-327077528_

@iSazonov Can you confirm that using the readonly-modifier in our case will not adversely affect types marked with `SerializableAttribute`?

> @xtqqczze Could you please revert changes I mentioned in previous comment in follow PR?

@iSazonov I am not so sure the changes are not a problem - they did not cause test failures after all. I'm been thinking that deserializers are usually implemented using reflection, so they can write to readonly fields.

Do you have specific concerns with the `SerializableAttribute` and readonly fields?

@PaulHigin Could you please help?
- Do we still need `SerializableAttribute` if we don't use BinarySerializer or we can remove them?
- Can we make fields readonly or we can break XML serializer?

> > Set readonly field via reflection doesn't work in .NET Core 3.0 and later versions, see https://stackoverflow.com/a/934942:
> > 
> > > In dotnet core 3.0 this is no longer possible. A System.FieldAccessException is thrown saying: "Cannot set initonly static field 'bar' after type 'Foo' is initialized."
> 
> @daxian-dbw I compiled and ran the code from https://stackoverflow.com/a/934944 with .NET Core 3.0, .NET Core 3.1 and .NET 5.0 and didn't see the `System.FieldAccessException`.
> 
> ```csharp
> using System;
> using System.Reflection;
> 
> public class Test
> {
>     private readonly string foo = "Foo";
> 
>     public static void Main()
>     {
>         Test test = new Test();
>         FieldInfo field = typeof(Test).GetField
>             ("foo", BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.NonPublic);
>         field.SetValue(test, "Hello");
>         Console.WriteLine(test.foo);
>     }        
> }
> ```
> 
> According to [SetValue documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/dotnet/api/system.reflection.fieldinfo.setvalue), if you attempt to set a value on a **static**, readonly field, an exception is thrown in .NET Core 3.0 and later.
> 
> See also:
> * https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/11571
> * https://github.com/dotnet/dotnet-api-docs/issues/3851

_Originally posted by @xtqqczze in https://github.com/PowerShell/PSReadLine/issues/1923#issuecomment-733533803_
